      <abstract>
        <p>Chromoblastomycosis is a chronic subcutaneous fungal infection caused by
traumatic implantation of dematiaceous fungi in the skin. The clinical
presentation is usually a verrucous plaque lesion and the diagnosis is
confirmed by the visualization of muriform bodies at direct examination or
at the histologic study. This report describes a rare case of tumoral
chromoblastomycosis confirmed by histologic study and whose agent was
identified by culture and micromorphology.</p>
      </abstract>
